    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <!-- § 1  — Laminate Metrology & Compensation Topology                 -->
    <!-- (Dynamic Scaling Compensation)                                    -->
    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <section class="f40-section">
      <div class="f40-section__inner">
        <h2 class="f40-section__number">§&thinsp;1</h2>
        <div class="f40-section__body">
          <h3 class="f40-section__title">Laminate Metrology &amp; Compensation Topology</h3>
          <p class="f40-section__summary">
            How we measure, model, and nullify the non-linear dimensional instability of 38 independent inner-layer cores before they are fused.
          </p>

          <div class="f40-two-col">
            <div class="f40-two-col__item">
              <h4 class="f40-two-col__heading">¶&thinsp;1.1 &mdash; The Measurement Baseline</h4>
              <p>
                Every inner-layer core entering a 40-layer build is scanned by a dual-head chromatic 
                confocal metrology system (Keyence LJ-X8000 series) at 16&thinsp;µm lateral resolution. 
                The scanner captures the <em>full-surface topography</em> of each core — not just 
                fiducial targets. Four registration targets per corner (16 total per panel) are located 
                with sub-2&thinsp;µm repeatability. The system outputs a 65,000+ point deformation 
                vector field per core that serves as the input to our compensation algorithm.
              </p>
              <p>
                Crucially, the measurement is performed <em>after</em> oxide treatment and 
                <em>after</em> the bake-out cycle (150°C for 90&thinsp;min), because the oxide 
                chemistry itself modifies copper surface tension and the bake removes adsorbed 
                moisture that would otherwise produce a false expansion reading.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-two-col__item">
              <h4 class="f40-two-col__heading">¶&thinsp;1.2 &mdash; Non-Uniform Compensation Grid</h4>
              <p>
                Rather than applying a single scaling factor per layer (which fails catastrophically 
                when copper density varies), our compensation engine tessellates each core into a 
                7×5 grid of 35 compensation zones. Each zone receives an independent fourth-order 
                polynomial warp function:</p>
              <div class="f40-formula">
                P'(x,y) = P(x,y) + Σᵢ₌₁⁴ Σⱼ₌₀ⁱ a<sub>ij</sub> · xⁱ⁻ʲ · yʲ
              </div>
              <p>
                where <em>a<sub>ij</sub></em> are the zone-specific coefficients computed from 
                the metrology scan. The Direct Imaging (LDI) system receives 38 separate warp 
                tables — one per inner layer — and applies them during the exposure pass. The 
                compensation upstreams to the NC drill file, which receives its own 40-layer 
                coordinate transform from the same model, ensuring via barrels land inside the 
                compensated pad centroids.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Verification:</strong> After final lamination, X-ray inspection measures 
                the residual offset at 32 predetermined locations across the panel. Lot 
                XF-40L-2406-017 yielded a mean residual of 19&thinsp;µm with a 3σ bound of 
                ±38&thinsp;µm — <em>measured, not modeled</em>.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <!-- § 2  — Sequential Lamination: Thermal Budget & Cycle Architecture -->
    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <section class="f40-section f40-section--alt">
      <div class="f40-section__inner">
        <h2 class="f40-section__number">§&thinsp;2</h2>
        <div class="f40-section__body">
          <h3 class="f40-section__title">Sequential Lamination: Thermal Budget &amp; Cycle Architecture</h3>
          <p class="f40-section__summary">
            A 40-layer stack cannot be pressed in a single operation. The laminate press cannot 
            cure 39 prepreg sheets uniformly — the thermal gradient from core to surface would 
            exceed 40°C, creating differential cure states and massive warpage. The solution is 
            a deliberately sequenced build-up.
          </p>

          <div class="f40-lam-cycle">
            <div class="f40-lam-cycle__visual">
              <div class="f40-lam-cycle__bar">
                <span class="f40-lam-cycle__phase" style="width: 18%;">Sub-core A<br><small>L1–L6</small></span>
                <span class="f40-lam-cycle__phase" style="width: 20%;">Sub-core B<br><small>L7–L14</small></span>
                <span class="f40-lam-cycle__phase" style="width: 20%;">Sub-core C<br><small>L15–L22</small></span>
                <span class="f40-lam-cycle__phase" style="width: 20%;">Sub-core D<br><small>L23–L30</small></span>
                <span class="f40-lam-cycle__phase" style="width: 18%;">Sub-core E<br><small>L31–L38</small></span>
                <span class="f40-lam-cycle__phase f40-lam-cycle__phase--final" style="width: 4%;">F<small><br>L39–40</small></span>
              </div>
              <div class="f40-lam-cycle__bar-labels">
                <span>Press 1</span>
                <span>Press 2</span>
                <span>Press 3</span>
                <span>Press 4</span>
                <span>Press 5</span>
                <span>Press 6</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-lam-cycle__detail">
              <p>
                <strong>Cycle sequence.</strong> Sub-cores A through E are each laminated at 
                190°C / 350&thinsp;psi with a 90-minute cure profile. After each press, the 
                sub-core is X-ray-inspected (see §&thinsp;6) and its compensation model is 
                updated before the next build-up step. The outer foils (L39–L40) are applied 
                in a final cap-layer press with a lower temperature profile (175°C) to preserve 
                the registration of the previously aligned sub-cores.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Thermal budget constraint.</strong> Each press cycle exposes the stack 
                to Tg+25°C for approximately 75 minutes. Over 6 cycles, the cumulative thermal 
                exposure exceeds 450 minutes above Tg. This is sufficient to fully cross-link 
                the resin system — but only if the resin chemistry is selected for <em>extended 
                cure latency</em>. Standard FR-4 resin will overcure and embrittle by the fourth 
                cycle, leading to Z-axis cracking during thermal stress testing.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>XFPCB material rule for 40 layers:</strong> Every prepreg in a 40-layer 
                stack must have a gel time ≥ 180 seconds at 171°C and a minimum cured Tg of 
                200°C (by DSC, IPC-TM-650 2.4.25). Materials failing these thresholds are 
                rejected at incoming QC. This rule alone eliminates approximately 60% of 
                commercially available prepregs from consideration.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <!-- § 3  — Copper Distribution Synthesis & Cross-Hatching Protocol    -->
    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <section class="f40-section">
      <div class="f40-section__inner">
        <h2 class="f40-section__number">§&thinsp;3</h2>
        <div class="f40-section__body">
          <h3 class="f40-section__title">Copper Distribution Synthesis &amp; Cross-Hatching Protocol</h3>
          <p class="f40-section__summary">
            Uneven copper distribution is the dominant root cause of 40-layer registration failure. 
            A solid copper plane on layer 17 and an empty routing channel on layer 18 produce 
            differential CTE behavior that no global compensation can fix. The solution is 
            <em>pre-lamination copper density equalization</em>.
          </p>

          <div class="f40-copper-grid">
            <div class="f40-copper-grid__item">
              <h4 class="f40-copper-grid__heading">¶&thinsp;3.1 &mdash; Density Threshold Enforcement</h4>
              <p>
                XFPCB enforces a per-layer copper density range of 40%–65% for all 38 inner 
                layers of any 40-layer build. If a customer's design violates this band, our 
                CAM engineers intervene in one of three ways:
              </p>
              <ul class="f40-list">
                <li><strong>Cross-hatching (preferred):</strong> Solid copper areas are 
                converted to a 75% fill cross-hatch pattern with 0.25&thinsp;mm trace / 
                0.25&thinsp;mm space. This reduces the local copper mass while maintaining 
                electrical continuity and impedance reference. The cross-hatch vectors are 
                aligned at 45° to the weave direction to minimize fiber-weave skew coupling.</li>
                <li><strong>Copper thieving (added):</strong> Low-density routing channels 
                receive non-functional copper thieving — electrically isolated square pads 
                (0.5&thinsp;mm × 0.5&thinsp;mm on 1.0&thinsp;mm pitch) that bring the local 
                density up to the 40% floor without affecting signal integrity.</li>
                <li><strong>Stackup redistribution (last resort):</strong> If layer-to-layer 
                density mismatch exceeds 30 percentage points, the stackup is re-ordered to 
                pair dense planes with dense planes and open channels with open channels.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-copper-grid__item">
              <h4 class="f40-copper-grid__heading">¶&thinsp;3.2 &mdash; Copper-Balance Impact on Registration</h4>
              <p>
                The mechanism linking copper density to registration is straightforward: copper 
                has a CTE of ~17&thinsp;ppm/°C (X/Y), while the FR-4/resin matrix has a CTE 
                of ~14–16&thinsp;ppm/°C below Tg and 60–80&thinsp;ppm/°C above Tg. A layer 
                with 80% copper is effectively copper-dominated (net CTE ~16.5&thinsp;ppm/°C). 
                A layer with 20% copper is resin-dominated (net CTE ~30&thinsp;ppm/°C above Tg). 
                When these two layers are bonded during lamination, the strain mismatch generates 
                a shear force that displaces the liquid-phase resin and physically shifts the 
                copper features.
              </p>
              <p>
                Our internal study (XF-R&D-023, 2023) measured the registration penalty of 
                unbalanced density pairs on a 40-layer test vehicle. A layer-to-layer copper 
                density delta of 40 percentage points produced a mean layer shift of 
                67&thinsp;µm — well beyond the ±38&thinsp;µm spec. Reducing the delta to 
                ≤20 points brought mean shift to 22&thinsp;µm. This data directly informs 
                the 40%–65% enforcement rule.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-copper-grid__item f40-copper-grid__item--wide">
              <h4 class="f40-copper-grid__heading">¶&thinsp;3.3 &mdash; Cross-Hatch Parameter Table</h4>
              <div class="f40-datasheet-table-wrapper">
                <table class="f40-datasheet-table">
                  <thead>
                    <tr><th>Copper Weight</th><th>Hatch Trace Width</th><th>Hatch Gap</th><th>Fill Factor</th><th>Min. Feature (etched)</th></tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr><td>0.5 oz (18&thinsp;µm)</td><td>0.15&thinsp;mm</td><td>0.15&thinsp;mm</td><td>50%</td><td>0.10&thinsp;mm</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>1.0 oz (35&thinsp;µm)</td><td>0.20&thinsp;mm</td><td>0.20&thinsp;mm</td><td>50%</td><td>0.12&thinsp;mm</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>2.0 oz (70&thinsp;µm)</td><td>0.30&thinsp;mm</td><td>0.30&thinsp;mm</td><td>50%</td><td>0.15&thinsp;mm</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>3.0 oz (105&thinsp;µm)</td><td>0.40&thinsp;mm</td><td>0.40&thinsp;mm</td><td>50%</td><td>0.20&thinsp;mm</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="f40-datasheet-table__footnote" colspan="5">All cross-hatch patterns oriented 45° to glass-weave direction. Post-etch dielectric standoff verified by microsection.</td></tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <!-- § 4  — Deep-Borehole Plating Physics (Ultra-Thick Drilling)       -->
    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <section class="f40-section f40-section--alt">
      <div class="f40-section__inner">
        <h2 class="f40-section__number">§&thinsp;4</h2>
        <div class="f40-section__body">
          <h3 class="f40-section__title">Deep-Borehole Plating Physics</h3>
          <p class="f40-section__summary">
            Drilling and plating a 0.3&thinsp;mm via through an 8.0&thinsp;mm stack (27:1 aspect 
            ratio) requires control over chip evacuation, spindle runout, electrolyte mass transport, 
            and current-density distribution that is fundamentally different from standard PCB 
            manufacturing.
          </p>

          <div class="f40-drill-grid">
            <div class="f40-drill-grid__item">
              <h4 class="f40-drill-grid__heading">¶&thinsp;4.1 &mdash; Mechanical Drilling Parameters</h4>
              <p>
                For 40-layer stacks ≥5.0&thinsp;mm, XFPCB uses a dedicated drilling protocol 
                distinct from standard production:
              </p>
              <ul class="f40-list">
                <li><strong>Spindle speed:</strong> 120–150&thinsp;kRPM (vs. 180–250&thinsp;kRPM for standard boards). Lower RPM reduces bit walk on entry and prevents drill-bit binding in the thick laminate.</li>
                <li><strong>Feed rate:</strong> 12–18&thinsp;µm/revolution, approximately half the standard rate. This limits the chip load and prevents glass-fiber pullout at the mid-span of the borehole.</li>
                <li><strong>Retract rate:</strong> 25&thinsp;m/min with peck cycles of 2.0&thinsp;mm depth. Active chip vacuum extraction at the spindle nozzle.</li>
                <li><strong>Entry &amp; exit material:</strong> 0.3&thinsp;mm aluminum entry board (not standard phenolic) to dissipulate heat; 1.0&thinsp;mm phenolic exit board to prevent exit burr formation.</li>
                <li><strong>Bit construction:</strong> Tungsten-carbide (6% cobalt binder) with a diamond-like carbon (DLC) coating. Standard bright-finish bits exhibit catastrophic wear after 800 hits at 8.0&thinsp;mm depth; DLC-coated bits maintain hole-wall quality for 2,500+ hits.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-drill-grid__item">
              <h4 class="f40-drill-grid__heading">¶&thinsp;4.2 &mdash; Periodic Reverse Pulse Plating (PRPP)</h4>
              <p>
                Standard DC electroplating produces a characteristic "dog-bone" profile in deep 
                vias — the copper thickness at the board surface is 3–5× thicker than at the 
                center of the borehole. At 27:1 aspect ratio, a DC process would yield an 
                unacceptably thin center-barrel wall (10–12&thinsp;µm vs. the IPC Class 3 
                minimum of 20&thinsp;µm average, 18&thinsp;µm minimum).
              </p>
              <p>
                XFPCB deploys periodic reverse pulse plating (PRPP) using the following 
                proprietary waveform:
              </p>
              <div class="f40-formula">
                J(t) = J<sub>cathodic</sub> (2.5 A/dm², 20&thinsp;ms) → J<sub>anodic</sub> (0.8 A/dm², 8&thinsp;ms) → J<sub>off</sub> (12&thinsp;ms) &nbsp;·&nbsp; repeat
              </div>
              <p>
                The anodic pulse periodically deplates copper from the high-current-density 
                regions at the via entrance, redistributing copper ions toward the borehole 
                center. The agitation is supplemented by air sparging at 6–8&thinsp;L/min and 
                ultrasonic transducers at 40&thinsp;kHz to disrupt the boundary layer at the 
                center of deep holes. The result is a barrel-wall thickness uniformity of 
                &lt;15% variation from surface to center, verified by microsection at 5 
                locations per hole.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Qualification data:</strong> Lot XF-40L-2406-017 included 12 test 
                coupons per panel with 0.3&thinsp;mm vias through 8.0&thinsp;mm board. 
                Cross-sectioning showed mean barrel thickness of 24&thinsp;µm (surface) to 
                21&thinsp;µm (center) — a 12.5% gradient against the IPC maximum allowable 
                of 50%.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-drill-grid__item f40-drill-grid__item--full">
              <h4 class="f40-drill-grid__heading">¶&thinsp;4.3 &mdash; Back-Drilling Protocol for Via-Stub Elimination</h4>
              <p>
                At 56&thinsp;Gbps and above, a via stub longer than 0.25&thinsp;mm introduces 
                a resonant null that attenuates the signal eye. For 40-layer backplanes routing 
                112&thinsp;Gbps PAM4, every via that transitions from an outer layer to an 
                inner layer must be back-drilled to within 0.10&thinsp;mm of the target layer. 
                XFPCB executes back-drilling with a dedicated secondary NC pass using a 
                0.40&thinsp;mm bit (0.05&thinsp;mm larger than the primary drill) at 
                100&thinsp;kRPM. Depth control is maintained via a contact-type depth sensor 
                with ±25&thinsp;µm repeatability. After back-drilling, 100% of vias are 
                inspected by air-gauging — if the residual stub exceeds 0.15&thinsp;mm, the 
                feature is flagged and a tertiary intervention bit is applied.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <!-- § 5  — Dielectric System Selection for 40-Layer Stacks            -->
    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <section class="f40-section">
      <div class="f40-section__inner">
        <h2 class="f40-section__number">§&thinsp;5</h2>
        <div class="f40-section__body">
          <h3 class="f40-section__title">Dielectric System Selection for 40-Layer Stacks</h3>
          <p class="f40-section__summary">
            The resin system in a 40-layer PCB must satisfy four competing constraints: 
            (1) survive &gt;450 cumulative minutes above Tg without overcuring; 
            (2) maintain a Df &lt; 0.005 at 10&thinsp;GHz for high-speed layers; 
            (3) wet-out 39 prepreg interfaces without voiding; and 
            (4) match the Z-axis CTE of the copper-filled vias to prevent barrel cracking. 
            No single dielectric satisfies all four. The solution is a <em>hybrid stackup</em>.
          </p>

          <div class="f40-datasheet-table-wrapper">
            <table class="f40-datasheet-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Material</th>
                  <th>Dk (10 GHz)</th>
                  <th>Df (10 GHz)</th>
                  <th>Tg (DSC)</th>
                  <th>Z-CTE (below/above Tg)</th>
                  <th>Max Lamination Cycles</th>
                  <th>Application in 40L Stack</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Megtron 7</strong> (Panasonic)</td>
                  <td>3.35</td>
                  <td>0.0013</td>
                  <td>230°C</td>
                  <td>40 / 160 ppm/°C</td>
                  <td>8+</td>
                  <td>High-speed signal layers (L2–L5, L36–L39)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Tachyon 100G</strong> (Isola)</td>
                  <td>3.02</td>
                  <td>0.0011</td>
                  <td>200°C</td>
                  <td>45 / 170 ppm/°C</td>
                  <td>6+</td>
                  <td>Very-high-speed serial lanes (L6–L12, L28–L34)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Astra MT77</strong> (Isola)</td>
