    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <!-- § 8  — Joint Engineering Protocol                                 -->
    <!-- ================================================================ -->
    <section class="f40-section f40-section--closing">
      <div class="f40-section__inner">
        <h2 class="f40-section__number">§&thinsp;8</h2>
        <div class="f40-section__body">
          <h3 class="f40-section__title">Joint Engineering Protocol</h3>
          <p class="f40-section__summary">
            A 40-layer PCB is not a catalog purchase. Every build begins with an engineering 
            review that spans stackup design, material selection, compensation modeling, and 
            test-vehicle qualification. Below is the standard engagement timeline.
          </p>

          <div class="f40-timeline">
            <div class="f40-timeline__entry">
              <span class="f40-timeline__phase">Week 1</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__label">Design &amp; DFM Review</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__desc">XFPCB CAM team reviews stackup, impedance targets, material selections, and copper density distribution. Preliminary compensation model is generated.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-timeline__entry">
              <span class="f40-timeline__phase">Week 2</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__label">EQ &amp; Stackup Sign-Off</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__desc">Engineering Query (EQ) report with detailed DFM recommendations, layer-by-layer compensation tables, resin-fill simulation results, and test-coupon layout. Customer approval required before fabrication.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-timeline__entry">
              <span class="f40-timeline__phase">Weeks 3–4</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__label">Sub-Core Fabrication &amp; X-Ray Verification</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__desc">Sub-cores A–C (Presses 1–3) are built, X-ray-inspected, and compensation is refined for subsequent cycles. Preliminary registration data shared with customer.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-timeline__entry">
              <span class="f40-timeline__phase">Weeks 5–6</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__label">Final Lamination &amp; Completion</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__desc">Presses 4–6, final drilling, PRPP plating, outer-layer imaging, solder mask, surface finish, and electrical test. Full X-ray registration certificate issued.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="f40-timeline__entry">
              <span class="f40-timeline__phase">Weeks 7–8</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__label">Qualification &amp; Shipment</span>
              <span class="f40-timeline__desc">TDR impedance verification, IST, microsection, thermal stress, and CAF testing. Lot Acceptance Test Report (LATR) shipped with product.</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="f40-cta">
            <p class="f40-cta__text">
              To initiate a joint engineering engagement, submit your stackup and Gerber files 
              through our dedicated engineering portal. A Senior CAM Architect will respond 
              within two business days with a preliminary DFM assessment and compensation 
              feasibility study.
            </p>
            <a href="#quote" class="f40-cta__button">Submit Design for Engineering Review</a>
            <p class="f40-cta__footnote">
              All submissions are treated under NDA. No engineering charge for initial DFM 
              review of qualifying 30+ layer designs.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
